WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.560
[Music] Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger.&nbsp;
In this video, we want to talk about this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.560 --> 00:00:21.080
fundamental symmetry that we've introduced into&nbsp;
mathematics. So the usual world of mathematical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:21.080 --> 00:00:30.160
objects is now augmented by a kind of alternate&nbsp;
mirrored world of anti-objects. And formally,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:30.160 --> 00:00:38.920
this is done very simply by just putting bars&nbsp;
over objects to denote the anti of an object.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:38.920 --> 00:00:46.600
This is going to be crucial for us in allowing&nbsp;
us to use the multiset framework to introduce&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.600 --> 00:00:53.440
negative multiplicities in a real sense, in a&nbsp;
concrete sense, rather than just formally and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:53.440 --> 00:01:00.760
just sort of waving our hands. So we actually&nbsp;
have objects that represent minus three cows,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:00.760 --> 00:01:06.760
or more typically, minus three pixels or&nbsp;
minus three singletons or minus three of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:06.760 --> 00:01:11.080
some particular mathematical object. It's going&nbsp;
to be very important for us when we want to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:11.080 --> 00:01:18.400
do abstract algebra and look at spaces, linear&nbsp;
spaces, groups, rings, fields in our next video.

00:01:18.400 --> 00:01:22.960
Okay, so the basic idea is: here are&nbsp;
our familiar kinds of objects that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:22.960 --> 00:01:28.400
we might want to use in mathematics, and&nbsp;
here are the corresponding anti-objects,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:33.640
which are just created by taking these objects&nbsp;
and putting bars over them. We're just following&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:33.640 --> 00:01:42.600
the physicists' usage here. So here's a number&nbsp;
three; here's anti-three or three-bar, and we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.600 --> 00:01:49.560
just take the actual object and put a bar over the&nbsp;
whole thing. And if we want to save space, or it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:49.560 --> 00:01:55.680
a little bit hard for us to put the bar over it,&nbsp;
we'll put the bar on the right-hand upper corner.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:55.680 --> 00:02:04.120
Here's our minus four number; here's the anti of&nbsp;
that minus four-bar; just take the object itself,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:04.120 --> 00:02:11.080
which is actually a bunch of anti-marks, and put&nbsp;
a bar over it. Here's a vexel, which is an M-set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:11.080 --> 00:02:21.040
of singletons; here's the anti V-bar. Here's an&nbsp;
ordered set S; it's got some different elements,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:21.040 --> 00:02:25.080
it's ordered because we see some commas.&nbsp;
Here is the corresponding anti-object;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:30.200
we just take the whole thing and put a bar&nbsp;
over it. We don't modify it in any way;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:30.200 --> 00:02:37.160
we just put a bar over the whole thing. Here's&nbsp;
a maxel consisting of a bunch of pixels;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:37.160 --> 00:02:43.800
here's the anti of that maxel, M-bar; just&nbsp;
take the whole thing and put a bar over it.

00:02:43.800 --> 00:02:48.040
So we have this fundamental symmetry,&nbsp;
which is really officially introduced&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:55.160
by this little equation that anti-mark times&nbsp;
some object, heart, whatever that might be,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:55.160 --> 00:03:01.640
as long as it's an actual specific object&nbsp;
that we've already nailed down, then this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:01.640 --> 00:03:10.760
product is going to be what we call heart-bar&nbsp;
or the anti-heart. And the crucial defining&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:10.760 --> 00:03:19.440
property of this anti-object is that if it and&nbsp;
the original object reside in an M-set together,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.440 --> 00:03:27.920
then they cancel. That means they both disappear&nbsp;
and they're replaced with nothing. So this is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:27.920 --> 00:03:32.520
not really a multiplication of heart times&nbsp;
heart-bar; this is just to denote that if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:32.520 --> 00:03:41.040
we have a heart and an anti-heart together in&nbsp;
the same M-set, then they are going to cancel.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.040 --> 00:03:47.840
And notice that it's crucial for us that we do&nbsp;
have a notion of nothing as being represented&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:47.840 --> 00:03:57.600
by a blank part of our page here to express&nbsp;
what happens when we combine these two things.

00:03:57.600 --> 00:04:02.280
So in today's video, we want to talk a little&nbsp;
bit more about this symmetry, get a little&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:02.280 --> 00:04:08.480
bit more experience with it, and then move to&nbsp;
seeing how it actually helps us in setting up&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:08.480 --> 00:04:16.320
a wider theory of vexels and maxels. Now, to get&nbsp;
a full symmetry between objects and anti-objects,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:23.040
we're going to want the anti of an anti-object&nbsp;
to be the original object. So we're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:28.840
introduce that as a definition. We're going&nbsp;
to say that when we take the anti of an anti,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:28.840 --> 00:04:35.200
we get the original. In other words,&nbsp;
if we take anti-mark times heart-bar,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:35.200 --> 00:04:41.560
which is the anti of the anti-heart—there's the&nbsp;
heart, there's the anti of it, and there's the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:41.560 --> 00:04:49.320
anti of the anti—we want that to be the same as&nbsp;
the original object, heart. So we're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:49.320 --> 00:04:56.880
introduce this as a definition, and this is&nbsp;
really consistent with our understanding that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.880 --> 00:05:04.240
anti-mark times anti-mark is mark, because&nbsp;
this thing here is anti-mark times heart-bar,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:04.240 --> 00:05:11.000
and this heart-bar is anti-mark times heart. And&nbsp;
what we're doing is we're saying let's agree that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:17.280
this thing is the same as this, and we're allowed&nbsp;
to use associativity at this level to rewrite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:17.280 --> 00:05:24.960
this as anti-mark times anti-mark times heart, in&nbsp;
which case we would get mark times heart, which we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:24.960 --> 00:05:34.120
know is heart. So the equality of this and this is&nbsp;
really equivalent to this associativity that we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:34.120 --> 00:05:44.880
allowing ourselves at the level of multiplication&nbsp;
of anti-marks with anti-marks with objects.

00:05:44.880 --> 00:05:52.320
Okay, and now we can introduce the idea of&nbsp;
the negative or negation of an M-set. This&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:58.640
is a very powerful thing to be able to do. Okay,&nbsp;
so we are now allowed to talk about an M-set and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:58.640 --> 00:06:07.800
its negative. How do we do that? Well, here's the&nbsp;
definition in a kind of abstract example. So if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:07.800 --> 00:06:14.240
here is an M-set, say heart, heart, diamond, and&nbsp;
these are some kind of mathematical objects that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:14.240 --> 00:06:22.400
we have agreed that we've already clearly&nbsp;
defined, then the negative of this M-set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:22.400 --> 00:06:28.720
which is what we get when we multiply by minus&nbsp;
one—here is the number minus one—then the way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:28.720 --> 00:06:34.440
we multiply M-sets is what we should do is we&nbsp;
should take the entries of this M-set and the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:34.440 --> 00:06:39.400
entries of this M-set and take all possible&nbsp;
products. So anti-mark times heart—well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:39.400 --> 00:06:43.360
that's heart-bar; anti-mark times this&nbsp;
heart—that's heart-bar; anti-mark times&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:43.360 --> 00:06:52.040
this diamond—that's diamond-bar. So the effect of&nbsp;
multiplying by minus one is to take the anti of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:52.040 --> 00:06:59.400
each of the original elements of the M-set,&nbsp;
go from M-set M to the M-set of its anti,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:00.240 --> 00:07:07.840
and that is the negative of the original&nbsp;
M-set. So negating an M-set means taking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:07.840 --> 00:07:16.400
the anti of all its entries. So we don't have to&nbsp;
do this now in a formal sense. Really, we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:16.400 --> 00:07:27.920
a rather specific idea and framework for talking&nbsp;
about combinations of M-sets, including negative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:27.920 --> 00:07:35.120
combinations. All right, so we can do things like&nbsp;
now not just add the M-set A plus the M-set B;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:35.120 --> 00:07:42.200
we can also take the M-set A minus the M-set&nbsp;
B, and we have a meaning to what that means.

00:07:42.200 --> 00:07:48.160
So here are some exercises for you to ponder&nbsp;
to practice your understanding of how these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:56.680
anti-objects interact with ordinary objects. So,&nbsp;
try to simplify these expressions if you can;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:56.680 --> 00:08:00.960
it might not be possible. So some of these&nbsp;
expressions might not actually make sense,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:00.960 --> 00:08:07.840
so you have to try to decide which ones do.&nbsp;
So here, for example, is a what's actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:07.840 --> 00:08:14.640
a singleton because it has a singleton one&nbsp;
in it, and here is another kind of object,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:14.640 --> 00:08:20.320
which has a singleton one-bar in it, and we want&nbsp;
to add those. Does that make sense, and if so,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:20.320 --> 00:08:25.600
what do we get? Here we have number two singleton&nbsp;
two, and here we have the anti of the singleton&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:31.400
two, which is subtly different from this&nbsp;
situation here. What happens there? Here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:31.400 --> 00:08:42.880
is the anti of M-set with inside a three-bar.&nbsp;
Here we have this M-set plus this M-set. Here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:48.440
we have the negation of this M-set, where this&nbsp;
one here contains a singleton four and the anti&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:48.440 --> 00:08:54.880
of the singleton five. Here we're adding the&nbsp;
anti of the singleton six and the anti of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.880 --> 00:09:01.720
singleton seven. Here we have an M-set consisting&nbsp;
of numbers zero, zero, one, and here's an M-set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:01.720 --> 00:09:12.920
consisting of integers one, minus two, and also&nbsp;
the anti. And here's a difference of two M-sets.

00:09:12.920 --> 00:09:19.280
So maybe we can also introduce some notational&nbsp;
convention. If we have to write this anti kind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:19.280 --> 00:09:24.480
of object in a typing kind of situation,&nbsp;
perhaps we could introduce the idea that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:24.480 --> 00:09:32.720
say, the pixel thirteen anti or thirteen&nbsp;
bar, we could write it perhaps like this:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:32.720 --> 00:09:39.960
anti of pixel thirteen. That's pretty unambiguous.&nbsp;
Or maybe we could write pixel thirteen and then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:39.960 --> 00:09:47.600
put a bar behind it, meaning this object&nbsp;
barred. Okay, so we could use bar or anti,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:47.600 --> 00:09:56.360
possibly, to convey this in a typed situation.&nbsp;
So here are some little things to think about.

00:09:56.360 --> 00:10:02.880
So one of the main things that we want to do with&nbsp;
these anti-objects is allow us to be a little bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:02.880 --> 00:10:08.800
more flexible about the use of M-sets. We want&nbsp;
to enlarge our notion of M-set now to include,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:08.800 --> 00:10:15.400
as we've seen, not just objects but also&nbsp;
anti-objects. And so we want to introduce a bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:15.400 --> 00:10:23.240
of terminology that captures that idea. So let's&nbsp;
talk about an integral M-set or an M-set. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:23.240 --> 00:10:29.920
so this is some kind of variant or slight&nbsp;
generalization of an M-set. And what is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:29.920 --> 00:10:36.680
an integral M-set? Well, suppose that&nbsp;
we have a notion of M-set of some type,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:36.680 --> 00:10:43.160
so we've decided on M-sets whose elements are of&nbsp;
a certain type, and we have a very clear idea of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:43.160 --> 00:10:50.920
what we're talking about in that context. Then&nbsp;
we'll consider IM-sets of that type to be, well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:50.920 --> 00:10:57.360
a more general kind of multiset that allows&nbsp;
not just the objects of the type that we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:57.360 --> 00:11:04.360
considering but also their antis, all right?&nbsp;
So that objects of the type we're considering,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:04.360 --> 00:11:11.120
as well as anti-objects of that type. So when&nbsp;
we allow both objects and anti-objects of a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:11.120 --> 00:11:21.520
given type, we'll talk about that as being an&nbsp;
integral M-set, or short, an IM-set of that type.

00:11:21.520 --> 00:11:25.960
So here's a very important illustration of&nbsp;
that; it's going to play a big role for us:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:25.960 --> 00:11:34.000
the idea of an integral vexel. So we've already&nbsp;
talked about vexels in the context of M-sets of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:42.280
singletons from, say, Nat, where, for example,&nbsp;
here is a vexel which has some singletons, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:42.280 --> 00:11:47.320
the singletons are from natural numbers. There's a&nbsp;
singleton zero, the singleton one, singleton one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:47.320 --> 00:11:54.520
singleton three—that's a vexel. And we've seen&nbsp;
that we can represent that vexel geometrically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:54.520 --> 00:12:04.360
or visually with this freeze-like object, where&nbsp;
we record the number of zero singletons in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:04.360 --> 00:12:11.480
special little box at the beginning—there's one of&nbsp;
them—and then record the number of one singletons,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:11.480 --> 00:12:17.040
the number of two singletons (there aren't&nbsp;
any), the number of three singletons, and this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:17.040 --> 00:12:23.040
is an open-ended kind of thing; the box doesn't&nbsp;
really end—it's possible for there to be further&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:23.040 --> 00:12:30.280
additions. And then we saw that we could extend&nbsp;
that idea once we have integers as well as natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:30.280 --> 00:12:38.840
numbers; we can think about using the integers to&nbsp;
specify an extended labeling structure. All right,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:38.840 --> 00:12:46.440
so we had vexel from integers; these are&nbsp;
M-sets of singletons from int. That means&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:46.440 --> 00:12:51.480
something like this, where we have singletons&nbsp;
whose entries are not just natural numbers but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:51.480 --> 00:12:57.880
also possibly negative numbers, so over the full&nbsp;
range of integers. And representing something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:57.880 --> 00:13:06.600
like this involves a similar kind of thing, but&nbsp;
now we're allowed to introduce multiplicities&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:06.600 --> 00:13:15.320
of the negatively labeled singletons. So here we&nbsp;
have a singleton minus two—there's one of them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:15.320 --> 00:13:21.520
so we put a one in the minus two spot. There's two&nbsp;
minus one singletons, so we put a two in the minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:21.520 --> 00:13:29.280
one spot. There's Z—Z singleton, so the special&nbsp;
box has a zero. There's zero one singleton,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:29.280 --> 00:13:34.480
and there's a single two singleton. So&nbsp;
we've used integers here crucially in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:34.480 --> 00:13:40.640
extending our vexel or vector point of view&nbsp;
from a one-sided story to a two-sided story;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:40.640 --> 00:13:48.640
that was important. And now we're going another&nbsp;
step up. Okay, so now we want to consider integer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:48.640 --> 00:13:54.760
vexels or integral vexels, and let's do that&nbsp;
in two stages. So first of all, from Nat,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:54.760 --> 00:14:00.880
where we consider IM-sets of singletons from&nbsp;
Nat, means we're back in this situation here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:00.880 --> 00:14:08.560
but now we're allowed to use not just singletons&nbsp;
but also anti-singletons. Okay, so here we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:08.560 --> 00:14:16.360
a singleton zero, a singleton zero, and here's&nbsp;
an anti-singleton one and a singleton two. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:16.360 --> 00:14:25.000
two singleton zeros are represented by this two&nbsp;
in the zero-labeled box. The anti-singleton one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:30.120
is represented by this minus one, right? So this&nbsp;
minus one now is telling us that instead of having&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:30.120 --> 00:14:39.240
one singleton one, we have minus one singleton&nbsp;
ones, which is the same for us as having a single&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:39.240 --> 00:14:49.880
anti-singleton one. So an anti-singleton one is&nbsp;
playing the role of minus one singleton ones,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:49.880 --> 00:14:55.960
and that singleton two is represented by that one&nbsp;
there. So the novelty now is that we're allowed to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:55.960 --> 00:15:03.520
put integers here, including negative numbers, and&nbsp;
the negative numbers that appear here are just a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:03.520 --> 00:15:11.480
reflection of the existence of anti-singletons&nbsp;
in the actual vexel that we're considering.

00:15:11.480 --> 00:15:20.080
And here's the more general thing, an integral&nbsp;
vexel from integers. Here we have a vexel which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:20.080 --> 00:15:26.760
contains singletons both with natural number&nbsp;
entries and also with negative number entries,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:26.760 --> 00:15:35.080
but we also have anti-singletons. So in this case,&nbsp;
what do we have? We have minus one singleton with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:35.080 --> 00:15:41.960
an anti and minus one singleton with the anti, so&nbsp;
there's minus two things altogether in the minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:41.960 --> 00:15:52.560
one box. There's a zero box, there's the minus&nbsp;
one box, there's minus two minus one singletons,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:52.560 --> 00:16:00.480
there's a zero zero singleton, there's a single&nbsp;
one singleton, and in terms of singleton twos,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:00.480 --> 00:16:08.240
there's minus one of them because there's a bar&nbsp;
over here. So here we're using integers in two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:08.240 --> 00:16:13.920
distinctly different ways: we're using integers,&nbsp;
first of all, to allow ourselves to index an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:13.920 --> 00:16:20.400
entire two-sided array of positions—position&nbsp;
zero, position one, position two, as well as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:20.400 --> 00:16:26.480
position minus one, position minus two, position&nbsp;
minus three, and so on. But we're also using&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:26.480 --> 00:16:34.520
integers to represent negative multiplicities,&nbsp;
like negative cows. Negative three cows—what does&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:34.520 --> 00:16:42.200
negative three cows mean? Well, we now know, in&nbsp;
the mathematical context at least, what it means;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:42.200 --> 00:16:48.760
it's like there's three anti-cows in our M-set. Of&nbsp;
course, we're not dealing with cows; we're dealing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:48.760 --> 00:16:55.960
with lists and sets and multisets and ordered&nbsp;
sets, these data type structures. And for us,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:55.960 --> 00:17:00.520
the anti-object is just what you get by&nbsp;
formally putting a bar over the object.

00:17:00.520 --> 00:17:06.560
So to summarize, we've now identified a new&nbsp;
framework for vectors, integral vectors from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:06.560 --> 00:17:15.960
integers. So these are IM-sets of singletons&nbsp;
from int. This is going to be our preferred&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:15.960 --> 00:17:22.320
overarching domain for doing vector arithmetic—in&nbsp;
other words, for doing linear algebra, in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:22.320 --> 00:17:30.280
for doing geometry. It's a very nice framework,&nbsp;
but now we know exactly what we're talking about.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:32.120 --> 00:17:37.480
At some point, we may actually go a little&nbsp;
bit further and up this a little bit to not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:37.480 --> 00:17:44.160
just having integer entries in our vexels—in&nbsp;
other words, when we write down a vector,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:44.160 --> 00:17:52.000
not just having integer entries, but also having&nbsp;
rational number entries, so once we get to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:58.600
stage of having an official version of rational&nbsp;
numbers. But currently, this is a very powerful&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:58.600 --> 00:18:02.480
framework. So typically, what we're talking&nbsp;
about is something that looks like this when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:02.480 --> 00:18:08.280
we represent it geometrically: there's a freeze,&nbsp;
it's two-sided, going to the left and right;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:08.280 --> 00:18:15.120
there's the special zero position, and the&nbsp;
actual entries now are integers representing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:15.120 --> 00:18:25.400
multiplicities of singletons, where the plus signs&nbsp;
would correspond to having honest singletons,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:25.400 --> 00:18:33.160
and the negative signs would correspond to&nbsp;
having anti-singletons. And necessarily,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:33.160 --> 00:18:39.520
these things are finite, because we are, I remind&nbsp;
you, always obliged to write things down fully.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:45.680
When we're talking about things precisely and&nbsp;
completely, we have to illustrate our concepts&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:45.680 --> 00:18:52.400
by writing things down completely and precisely,&nbsp;
so no going off to infinity at this stage. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:52.400 --> 00:19:00.720
so an actual object of this has to be written down&nbsp;
entry by entry by entry, all of it there. And it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:00.720 --> 00:19:09.560
really a short form for a corresponding M-set&nbsp;
or IM-set. So these are two-sided, open-ended&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:09.560 --> 00:19:17.760
vectors with integral entries, and they correspond&nbsp;
to IM-sets of singletons from int. We're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:17.760 --> 00:19:24.960
say this is a lovely framework for thinking about&nbsp;
geometry and linear algebra in a very big way.

00:19:24.960 --> 00:19:32.360
And another main example for us is integral&nbsp;
maxels. So we started off talking about maxels&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:32.360 --> 00:19:39.880
as M-sets of pixels from natural numbers, and then&nbsp;
we enlarged that to consider maxels as M-sets of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:39.880 --> 00:19:48.440
pixels from integers. For example, here's a maxel&nbsp;
with these three pixels: zero, minus one; zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:48.440 --> 00:19:58.000
minus one; one, two. And that corresponds to this&nbsp;
geometric grid kind of view, where this is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:06.320
zero zero position. It's the one zero, two zero,&nbsp;
three zero over here; zero zero, zero one, zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:06.320 --> 00:20:13.520
two, zero three; but now also zero minus one, zero&nbsp;
minus two. So this two here is representing the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:13.520 --> 00:20:22.840
fact that we have two zero minus one pixels, and&nbsp;
there's a single one two pixel. Okay, now we want&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:22.840 --> 00:20:30.320
to extend this by going to integral maxels. First&nbsp;
of all, integral maxels—these would be IM-sets of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:30.320 --> 00:20:40.800
pixels from natural numbers, just the same kind&nbsp;
of sort of limited freeze that just works with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:40.800 --> 00:20:46.960
a quadrant. But more interestingly, integral&nbsp;
maxels from int. So these are M-sets of pixels&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:46.960 --> 00:20:52.560
from integers. So these are just like these ones,&nbsp;
except now we're also allowed the possibility of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:52.560 --> 00:20:59.480
having anti-pixels as well as pixels. So here's&nbsp;
N, which looks quite a bit like this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:59.480 --> 00:21:05.720
except that instead of having these two pixels,&nbsp;
it has their corresponding anti-pixels. So instead&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:05.720 --> 00:21:13.200
of having a two in this position, in this zero&nbsp;
minus one position, we have a minus two, because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:13.200 --> 00:21:20.200
there's these two anti-pixels, and we still have&nbsp;
a single honest pixel one two represented by that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:20.200 --> 00:21:28.680
one there. So now we're in a position to deal with&nbsp;
matrices with integer values, and matrices which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:28.680 --> 00:21:38.600
are very general—that they have entries covering&nbsp;
the entire plane. It's a very general, beautiful&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:38.600 --> 00:21:46.520
framework for doing matrix theory and linear&nbsp;
algebra and other things as well, as we'll see.

00:21:46.520 --> 00:21:53.120
Okay, so we are now in a great position&nbsp;
because these integral points of view,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:53.120 --> 00:21:58.960
these integral M-sets that we now have at&nbsp;
our disposal, allow us entry to a lot of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:58.960 --> 00:22:07.920
abstract algebra. So we're able to now, in a&nbsp;
more precise fashion than we currently have,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:07.920 --> 00:22:19.600
start talking about abstract algebra notions,&nbsp;
such as groups, rings, fields, vector spaces,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:19.600 --> 00:22:30.120
modules, and other things, in a more precise,&nbsp;
careful, concrete manner. In the next video,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:30.120 --> 00:22:34.760
I want to start that by giving&nbsp;
an overview of abstract algebra,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:34.760 --> 00:22:42.080
a bird's-eye picture of abstract algebra. It's&nbsp;
a relatively modern mathematical development,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:42.080 --> 00:22:47.360
roughly 100 years old, and which is now&nbsp;
very, very extensive. But I want to give&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:47.360 --> 00:22:55.200
you an introduction to this, and then we'll be&nbsp;
in a good position to start using this concrete,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:55.200 --> 00:23:04.960
precise way of thinking about data structures to&nbsp;
